SYNOPSIS
        #include <websocket.h>

        int websocket_init_connection(object ob)
        int websocket_init_connection(object ob, string fun,
                                      string|object fob, mixed extra...)
        int websocket_init_connection(object ob, closure fun, mixed extra...)

DESCRIPTION
        websocket_init_connection() initiates a WebSocket handshake on
        the interactive object <ob> (or this_object() if <ob> is not
        given).

        The connection enters the WS_HANDSHAKING state and waits for
        the client to send an HTTP upgrade request. Once the handshake
        completes successfully, the connection transitions to WS_ACTIVE
        and all subsequent I/O is WebSocket-framed.

        Telnet negotiation is disabled for WebSocket connections.

        Result:
          0: Handshake is in progress (waiting for client data).
         -1: Error (object not interactive, or already in WebSocket mode).

        If the callback <fun>/<fun>:<fob> is specified, it will be
        called once the WebSocket handshake completes. The first argument
        will be the result (0 on success), followed by the interactive
        object <ob> and any <extra> arguments.

        In most cases, auto-detection is preferred over calling this efun
        directly. The driver automatically detects WebSocket connections
        by inspecting the first bytes of incoming data for an HTTP GET
        request. See the websocket(C) concept page for details.

NOTES
        During the WebSocket handshake, nothing else should be sent to
        the client. The handshake is an HTTP request/response exchange,
        and any data sent before the 101 response would confuse the
        client.

        For secure WebSocket (WSS) connections, call
        tls_init_connection() first to establish TLS, then use
        websocket_init_connection() or rely on auto-detection.

